  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most common questions vendors ask before listing is how much to spend preparing the property. The instinct is often to renovate, and sometimes that instinct is right. But the data on comparable sales in Brisbane's inner east consistently shows that styling and targeted presentation work delivers a higher return per dollar spent than most renovation projects. Understanding why helps you make better decisions with the money you have available before your campaign begins.</p>

      <p>The short version: professional styling and cosmetic improvements almost always pay for themselves and more. Full kitchen and bathroom renovations before sale rarely do, unless the property is genuinely unmortgageable or unliveable in its current state. The buyers who buy renovated properties are typically paying a renovated-property price regardless of when the work was done. If you renovate to sell, you are often doing expensive work at someone else's timing and taste risk.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers actually notice</h2>
      <p>Buyers form a first impression within seconds of walking through a door. That impression is driven overwhelmingly by cleanliness, smell, light, and space, not by the age of the kitchen appliances or whether the bathroom has been retiled. A property that is spotlessly clean, well-lit, decluttered, and coherently styled will almost always outperform a renovated property that feels cluttered, dark, or staged without care.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, buyers in the $900,000 to $1.8 million price range are typically experienced. They have attended dozens of open homes. They know what a well-styled property looks like versus a genuinely improved one. They also know that cosmetic styling does not change the bones of a property. What styling does is reduce the mental discount buyers apply when they imagine living there. A home that photographs beautifully, presents coherently, and feels spacious generates more emotional engagement, more competition between buyers, and stronger offers.</p>

      <p>Renovation, by contrast, signals to buyers that work has been done but also raises questions: what was the quality of the work, what was the motivation for doing it before sale, and what lies beneath the new surfaces? A fresh kitchen can increase perceived value, but it can also trigger scrutiny that would not have existed otherwise.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where to spend before selling: the quick wins</h2>
      <p>The highest-return pre-sale investments in Brisbane's inner-east market are consistently the same. Paint is almost always worth doing, particularly on the exterior and on any rooms with dated or dark wall colours. Fresh neutral paint makes a property feel newer and photographing better. The cost for a house is typically $4,000 to $10,000 depending on size, and the return in comparable sales is reliably higher than that.</p>

      <p>Landscaping and garden presentation have an outsized effect on first impressions and street appeal. A neglected garden sends a message about the care taken with the property overall. A day's work by a good landscaper, fresh mulch, trimmed edges, and pressure-washed paths can transform a tired property's curb appeal for under $1,500. In a suburb like Hawthorne or Bulimba where buyers are walking in from tree-lined streets expecting a certain standard, this investment is non-negotiable.</p>

      <p>A thorough professional clean, including carpets and windows, is the cheapest intervention with some of the most reliable impact. Buyers notice smell and grime immediately and subconsciously discount accordingly. A property that is clean to a hotel standard communicates care and maintenance in a way that no renovation can replicate.</p>

      <p>Minor repairs matter too: the leaking tap, the cracked ceiling rose, the gate that does not close properly. Each one is a small negative that compounds in a buyer's mind during an inspection. Buyers use these items as justifications for lower offers. Fixing them costs little but removes those justifications.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Professional styling: the case for it</h2>
      <p>Professional property styling, where a stylist replaces or supplements your furniture with hire pieces for the campaign period, is well established in Brisbane and the data supports it. For a typical inner-east house, styling costs between $3,000 and $7,000 for a four-week campaign. The return in comparable sales is consistently higher.</p>

      <p>Styling works for two reasons. First, it makes the photography better, and photography drives your initial online impression, which drives attendance at inspections. Second, it makes buyers feel a genuine emotional connection to the space. When a buyer can see themselves living in a coherently presented home, they are more motivated and more willing to compete. Competition is what produces strong prices.</p>

      <p>Styling is particularly important for vacant properties, properties with dated or mismatched furniture, and properties where the current occupants have heavily personalised the decor. Buyers have difficulty mentally neutralising a space that is full of someone else's things.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When renovation makes sense before sale</h2>
      <p>There are situations where renovation before sale is the right call. If the kitchen is genuinely dysfunctional, with non-working appliances, damaged cabinetry, or a layout that buyers will want to change entirely, a modest update can prevent the property from being passed over by buyers who see it as too much work. The key word is modest: new benchtops, updated tapware, and fresh cabinet doors often achieve more than a full kitchen replacement for a fraction of the cost.</p>

      <p>Similarly, if the property has structural issues that will appear on a building report and trigger price renegotiation, addressing them before sale is usually more cost-effective than trying to sell with a known defect. Buyers who identify a structural problem discount by more than the actual repair cost, because they are also pricing in inconvenience, uncertainty, and the risk that it is worse than it looks.</p>

      <p>The properties where pre-sale renovation reliably adds value are those being sold into a price bracket where buyers expect renovation to have been done. A fibro cottage in a suburb with median sales of $1.5 million for renovated properties may struggle to achieve that median without some investment. But even then, the renovation should be targeted at the elements buyers in that price bracket care about most: kitchen, bathrooms, and primary bedroom. Full whole-house renovations before sale almost never return dollar for dollar.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The rule of thumb</h2>
      <p>If you are unsure where to spend, start with the cheapest interventions and work up only to the point where the expected return justifies the cost. Clean, paint, style, fix minor defects, and address garden presentation before you consider any structural work or room renovations. Get an honest assessment from your agent of what comparable sales suggest about whether buyers are paying a premium for the renovated versus unrenovated version of your property type in your suburb. That comparison will tell you more reliably than gut instinct whether renovation is worth the time, money, and disruption before your campaign.</p>

